Architecture plan for issues #77-#85

Current structure
- React/Vite/TypeScript SPA with React Three Fiber and Three.js for the face viewport.
- src/layout composes the dashboard regions; src/components contains controls, viewport, readout, footer/hero, and shared UI.
- src/state owns the global Zustand control readout: active pose label, control mode, frame index, and activation values.
- src/domain/poses contains preset definitions, keyboard mappings, morph target aliasing, and compatibility audits.
- src/domain/providers defines the deformation provider interface and the current kinematic blendshape provider.
- src/domain/precompute contains keyboard transition warmup/cache logic.

Issue dependency order
1. #77 should remove runtime hair and procedural tongue rendering from src/components/viewport/face-viewport.tsx and related props/state usage.
2. #78 should simplify src/components/viewport/gltf-head-loader.ts by removing texture loading, material transfer, projection UV generation, and tongue-geometry diagnostics, leaving only glTF loading, morph target discovery, normalization, and blendshape apply/read methods.
3. #79 should remove texture/projection env configuration and UI wiring from src/config/env.ts, src/layout/dashboard-layout.tsx, src/layout/dashboard-regions.tsx, and controls; this depends on #77/#78 removing consumers.
4. #80 should delete orphaned texture/projection/hair/tongue modules, public texture assets, and obsolete tests after imports are gone.
5. #81 should update pose data by removing tongueOut from the T phoneme and clearing any partial preset state caused by the removed tongue dependency.
6. #82 should manually/automatically verify all presets deform visibly on the default facecap mesh and adjust weights/aliases where needed.
7. #83 should strengthen E2E/unit tests so preset assertions check visible/live deformation, not only readout text.
8. #84 should update docs/system-overleaf.tex to match the simplified no-texture/no-material-transfer architecture.
9. #85 should run full regression and visual verification after all removals and test updates land.

Key design decisions
- Keep the deformation provider contract stable: controls dispatch normalized blendshape weights; viewport runtime evaluates provider frames and applies weights to mesh morph targets.
- Do not replace removed hair/tongue/texture features with placeholders unless a later issue explicitly asks; the simplified viewport should focus on the loaded head mesh and blendshape deformation.
- Treat config removals as breaking changes to env parsing only after all consumers are removed, so intermediate branches remain buildable.
- Preserve the pose library, alias resolver, audit system, keyboard precompute cache, and readout/curve panels as the core product surface.
- Tests should favor user-observable deformation state: active non-zero morph influences, canvas/runtime diagnostics, or numeric activation rows tied to actual default mesh compatibility.
